Space Fight

by: Hailin Day

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make a game like this because I always thought that this style of topdown game was awesome. So I decided to make a game similar to the one I had previously made with instructions. But remodeling everything to look better and adding more features, enemies and goals to the game. I ended up making a very basic game but a type of game that I would love to remake once I understand coding better.

2. What I Learned

I did not actually have user testing as I did this game during online classes. So I had no peers to share it with.

3. Architecture of My Game

The main focus of my code was the GamePanel class as it is where I wrote all of the code creating the menus and switching between each of the games current states (menu, instructions, game, end, win). It is where I would compile everything together and format it nicely. In the ObjectManager class, I set all of the moving aspects of the game to have collision boxes and what they will do when they collide with a specific different object. Every class is eventually compiled into the GamePanel for all of the aspects to occur inside of the game.

4. Technical Implementation

Some of the many technical implementations in my game include movement, firing projectiles, random enemy spawns, and music. I used if statements to create all of the movement, as well as setting how many pixels would be shifted when each button is pressed. Firing projectiles was more complex with me having to code in the collision of the projectiles with other objects. I am most proud of the music because I was able to figure out how to use my previous lessons code in order to make a fully functioning sound system within the game. Having sounds play with different actions.

5. Most Challenging Part

The most challenging part of this project was probably making the enemies projectiles random spawn work correctly. I struggled a lot with trying to make them spawn at a random place at a consistent time. Sometimes they would spawn way too quickly and not consistently, sometimes they wouldn't spawn at all. But i got it to work eventually.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

I would like to add animations/gifs as the avatars instead as right now, it looks extremely bland, with objects only moving in the four linear directions. It would maybe be cool to have one of the enemies weapons shoot at a random angle across the screen.
